variable, you also

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:44.990
have the notion of
a derivative there.

00:01:44.990 --> 00:01:50.500
And then, the derivative
is much more miraculous

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:54.460
than it is here in
the setting of r.

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:56.200
But the whole point
is, the derivative

00:01:56.200 --> 00:01:59.050
is something of a miracle.

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:03.130
So today, the goal is
to prove some properties

00:02:03.130 --> 00:02:04.150
about the derivatives.

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:06.792
Most of these you know.

00:02:06.792 --> 00:02:08.500
Maybe you didn't cover
the proofs of them

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:14.500
in calculus with the ultimate
goal of proving the mean value

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:23.080
theorem, which
is, to me probably

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.440
the most underappreciated
but most important

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:28.610
result in calculus.

00:02:28.610 --> 00:02:32.200
Now, you could
argue that probably

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:33.925
the hero of the
story of calculus

00:02:33.925 --> 00:02:35.800
is the fundamental
theorem of calculus, which

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:38.140
connects integration,
which we'll cover next

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:39.980
after differentiation.

00:02:39.980 --> 00:02:42.310
Which so the fundamental
theorem of calculus

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:46.320
connects integration
and differentiation.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:47.720
So that really is, but--

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:49.850
and that is really
the hero of calculus.

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:55.220
It gets used more
than anything else.

00:02:55.220 --> 00:03:00.890
But to prove that, you use
the mean value theorem.

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:06.093
So if the fundamental theorem
of calculus was Batman,

00:03:06.093 --> 00:03:07.510
I would say the
mean value theorem

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:09.460
is something like Alfred.

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:12.730
He's really the reason why
Batman gets to be who he is.

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:17.170
Enough analogies for now.

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:23.100
Let's go back to proving some
properties of the derivative.

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:30.902
So first, let's do some basic--

00:03:30.902 --> 00:03:35.310
the basic linearity and
rules for the derivative.

00:03:35.310 --> 00:03:43.505
So let f go from I to R.
i is always some interval.

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:57.990
And if f-- so I have
two functions, f and g,

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:00.382
from I to R. c is a point in i.

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:17.200
And the conclusion is, if f
and g are differentiable at c,

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:22.570
then we have several
rules that we can apply.

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:31.730
The first is basically the
linearity of the derivative

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:38.870
that for all alpha and
R, function alpha f plus

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:49.910
g, which now goes from I to
R, is differentiable at c.

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:58.040
And the derivative of the
function alpha f plus g

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:04.520
prime c is alpha times f
prime of c plus g prime of c.

00:05:09.575 --> 00:05:14.340
I think I'm starting to write
a little slandered here.

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:24.300
Second is the multiplication
rule, which is the function

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:34.460
f times g is
differentiable at c.

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:41.030
And the derivative
of the product

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:42.920
is not the product
of the derivatives,

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:50.270
but the prime of c, g of c
plus f of c, g prime of c.

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:55.740
So that's a multiplication rule.

00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:58.020
And then, we also have
the quotient rule.

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:13.040
And just like when you need
to divide by something,

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:17.270
you need to assume that
you're never dividing by 0.

00:06:17.270 --> 00:06:24.560
If g of x does not
equal 0 for all x in I,

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:40.710
then the function f over
g is differentiable at c.

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:48.910
And the derivative
is the derivative

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:53.950
of the top times the
bottom minus the top

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:58.210
times the derivative of
the bottom over the bottom

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:04.450
squared, [? now ?]
prime g of c squared.

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:10.480
So I'll prove one and two.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:13.030
Three we'll leave
as an exercise.

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:33.700
So for one, we just
compute that the limit

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:45.070
as x goes to c of alpha f plus g
of x, minus alpha f plus g of c

00:07:45.070 --> 00:07:53.040
over x minus c, this is just
by definition alpha times

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:57.990
f of x plus g of x minus alpha
times f of c plus g of c.

00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:02.790
And so, this equals the
limit as x goes to c.

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:07.020
And just collecting
terms alpha times alpha

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:15.480
f of x minus f of c times
x minus c, plus g of x

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:20.280
minus g of c over x minus c.

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:27.790
And all of these limits exist.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:29.230
So this is just a fixed number.

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:33.100
The limit as x goes to c of
this exists and this exists.

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:36.419
So by what we know
about limits, namely

00:08:36.419 --> 00:08:40.929
that the limit of the sum
is the sum of the limits.

00:08:40.929 --> 00:08:43.090
And then, scalars just
pull out of the limit.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:49.900
This is equal to alpha times f
prime of c plus g prime of c.

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:52.750
So that's the proof
of the first one.

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:56.590
For the proof of the
second one, we'll

00:08:56.590 --> 00:09:00.490
use the fact that
a function which

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:06.110
is differentiable at a point
is also continuous at a point.

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:21.880
So since g is differentiable
at c, it is continuous at c.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:23.350
I.e.

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:29.350
limit as x goes to c of
g of x equals g of c.

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:34.930
Now we compute the
limit as x goes

00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:42.310
to c of f times g
of x minus f of c

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:45.700
times g of c over x minus c.

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:52.120
Now what I'm going to
do is add and subtract

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:54.790
f of c times g of x.

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:57.340
So this I can write
as the limit as x

00:09:57.340 --> 00:10:06.070
goes to c of f of x, minus f of
c over x minus c, times g of x.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:22.640
Plus now, f of c times g of x
minus g of c over x minus c.

00:10:26.230 --> 00:10:30.250
And again, so this limit
as x goes to c exists.

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:34.090
This is just the
derivative of f at c.

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:36.655
And we noted that since
g is differentiable at c,

00:10:36.655 --> 00:10:39.130
g is also continuous
at c, meaning the limit

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.280
as x goes to c of g
of x equals g of c.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:43.900
This is just a constant f of c.

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:45.610
This goes to g prime of c.

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:48.610
So all these limits exist.

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:50.410
And therefore, we
get that this is

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:59.500
equal to f prime of c times g
of c plus f of c, g prime of c.

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.540
And three, I'll
leave as an exercise.

00:11:05.450 --> 00:11:07.220
Again, you'll write out--

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:12.110
you'll add and
subtract something

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:16.550
to f of x over g of x
minus f of c over g of c

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:20.090
and use the fact that
differentiability at a point

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:22.970
implies continuity, and
just evaluate the limits.

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:26.030
So I'm going to stop
with these two rules.

00:11:32.412 --> 00:11:34.620
I don't know why I called
it the multiplication rule.

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:36.230
It's called the product rule--

00:11:36.230 --> 00:11:39.020
well, multiplication and
product are the same thing.

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:47.800
But we also have the
chain rule, which

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:54.340
requires a little more care
to prove than what we've

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:57.310
done so far for these rules.

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:03.550
So suppose I have two intervals.

00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:15.130
And then I have a function
g going from I1 to I2,

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:25.740
f going from I2 to
R. And suppose g

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:39.160
is differentiable at c, and f
is differentiable at g of c.

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:58.800
Then the function f of g,
function goes from I1 to R.

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:02.850
This is differentiable at c.

00:13:02.850 --> 00:13:16.330
And the derivative
equals f prime of g of c

00:13:16.330 --> 00:13:19.030
times g prime of c.

00:13:38.270 --> 00:13:51.170
So what's the basic idea?

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:58.310
Again, so this is basic idea
is that we write the difference

00:13:58.310 --> 00:14:11.530
quotient, g of x minus f of g of
c over x minus c as f of g of x

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:19.460
minus g, f at g
of c times over g

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:31.080
of x minus g of c times g of
x over g of c times x minus c.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:35.190
And let x go to c,
and then we'll pick up

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:37.200
the derivative of g here at c.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:41.970
And right here, this is f of
something converging to g of c.

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:45.150
And so, this should be
like f prime of g of c.

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:48.120
But the only problem with
really writing this down

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:51.720
is that there could be points
where g of x equals g of c.

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:53.040
And then, I'm dividing by 0.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:54.210
That's not allowed.

00:14:54.210 --> 00:14:59.310
So writing this
expression is meaningless.

00:14:59.310 --> 00:15:02.250
But we're going to do
something like this in spirit,

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:06.360
where at least when g of
x does not equal g of c,

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:08.430
this thing kind of
equals this thing.

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:14.945
That's the basic idea.

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:27.420
So to implement
this strategy, let's

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:31.810
introduce some notation and
a few auxiliary functions.

00:15:31.810 --> 00:15:38.760
So first off, the function
we're interested in taking

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:41.040
the derivative f of g,
let me call that h of x.

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:47.610
Because I don't want to have
to keep writing f of g of x.

00:15:47.610 --> 00:15:48.720
Let's call it d.

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:52.340
This will be the point g of c.

00:15:52.340 --> 00:16:02.610
So we want to show
then that h prime of c

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:08.460
exists, and it's equal to f
prime of d times g prime of c.

00:16:12.180 --> 00:16:14.970
Just in this
notation I've set up.

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:23.600
So now, let me define some
auxiliary functions u of y.

00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:29.030
This is going to be essentially
the difference quotient of f,

00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:30.920
except at a certain point.

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:35.990
So this is f of y
minus f of d over y

00:16:35.990 --> 00:16:42.390
minus d when y does not equal
d so that this is meaningful.

00:16:42.390 --> 00:16:47.690
And then, f prime of
d when y equals d.

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:50.840
And then, v of x--

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:55.580
so this is going to play the
role of that first expression

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:58.070
I wrote up there, f of g
of x minus f of g of c.

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:04.760
And then, v of x,
this will be g of x

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:12.170
minus g of c, x minus c
when x does not equal c,

00:17:12.170 --> 00:17:16.460
and g prime of c
when x equals c.

00:17:19.670 --> 00:17:33.000
Now, essentially
what do we have here?

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:42.030
Then if I look at f
of y minus f of d,

00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:49.020
this is equal to u of y
times y minus d, always.

00:17:49.020 --> 00:17:53.640
Because if y does not equal
d, then I divide over,

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:57.240
and I get u of y,
then I get f of y

00:17:57.240 --> 00:17:59.790
minus f of d on the left-hand
side over y minus d.

00:17:59.790 --> 00:18:02.440
And that's equal to
u of y by definition.

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:06.900
And then, when y equals d, I get
0 here, and I get 0 over here.

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:09.060
So that's clear.

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:14.910
And also, the same here,
g of x minus g of c

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:19.590
equals v of x minus
[INAUDIBLE] times x minus c.

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:32.075
So we have these
two expressions.

00:18:32.075 --> 00:18:33.450
And one more thing
I want to note

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:36.570
is that u and v are
continuous at y equals

00:18:36.570 --> 00:18:39.690
d and x equals c respectively.

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:53.230
So note that v of y
is continuous at d,

00:18:53.230 --> 00:18:59.050
and v of x is continuous at c.

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:01.810
So let's look at
the proof of that.

00:19:01.810 --> 00:19:06.330
We just need to show that the
limit as y goes to d of v of y

00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:07.710
equals v of d.

00:19:07.710 --> 00:19:12.480
So compute the limit as
y goes to d of v of y.

00:19:12.480 --> 00:19:16.740
Now, when we look
at limits, remember,

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:19.590
we're not allowed
to put y equals

00:19:19.590 --> 00:19:23.280
d in the expression
for this limit.

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:27.000
We're always looking at points
y close to d but not equal to d,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.810
is what I'm saying.

00:19:28.810 --> 00:19:32.670
And so, therefore, when y is
near d, and not equal to d,

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:35.910
v of y is given by--

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:37.081
I should-- this should--

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:42.110
I should have written
u here, sorry, u.

00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:50.250
So we're looking at y near
d, but not equal to d.

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:53.220
And therefore, it's
given by this expression.

00:19:53.220 --> 00:19:55.590
So this is the
limit as y goes to d

00:19:55.590 --> 00:20:00.420
of f of y minus f
of d over y minus d.

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:05.820
And this is just the definition
of the derivative of f at d.

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:07.290
So remember, d is g of c.

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:08.970
So f is differentiable there.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:14.340
And this is by
definition u of d.

00:20:14.340 --> 00:20:20.790
So this function u is
continuous at y equals d.

00:20:20.790 --> 00:20:30.540
And similarly, the limit as
x goes to c of u of x, v of x

00:20:30.540 --> 00:20:37.940
equals v of c, which
is g prime of c.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:46.250
So now we're going to combine
what I've written here

00:20:46.250 --> 00:20:48.110
to finish the proof.

00:20:48.110 --> 00:21:00.560
So in h of x minus
h of c, this is

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:08.620
equal to f of g of
x minus f of g of c.

00:21:08.620 --> 00:21:20.650
And this is equal to u of g of
x times g of x minus g of c.

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:24.650
This is from this relation here.

00:21:24.650 --> 00:21:31.940
So we'll call this one
star, this one double star.

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:32.705
This is by star.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:45.640
And now, I use the second
relation, double star,

00:21:45.640 --> 00:21:55.330
to write g of x minus g of c
equals v of x times x minus c.

00:21:55.330 --> 00:22:00.030
And therefore, the
limit as x goes

00:22:00.030 --> 00:22:11.960
to c of h of x minus h
of c, or x minus c, this

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:16.130
is equal to the
limit as x goes to c

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:21.350
of u of g of x times v of x.

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:28.700
Now, u is continuous at g
of c, g is continuous at c.

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:30.620
And we proved that
the composition

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:33.680
of two continuous
functions is continuous.

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:41.720
So this equals u of g of c.

00:22:41.720 --> 00:22:43.850
And v of x, we've
proven already.

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:47.060
That limit is v of c.

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:51.020
And u of g of c, so
this is d, remember,

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:52.940
in the notation we had earlier.

00:22:52.940 --> 00:22:59.400
And therefore, that
equals f prime of g of c.

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:06.910
Remember, g of c was
d, times g prime of c.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:14.680
So to go from this
point to this point,

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:16.920
we use the fact that
u is continuous at c,

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:19.020
which we proved.

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:23.320
u is continuous at g of c,
which we proved over there.

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:27.633
And that g is continuous at c.

00:23:27.633 --> 00:23:30.050
And therefore, the composition
of two continuous functions

00:23:30.050 --> 00:23:35.572
is continuous at that point
to arrive at this guy.

00:23:35.572 --> 00:23:37.030
But again, the
whole basic idea was

00:23:37.030 --> 00:23:38.560
to be able to write
the difference

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:44.290
quotient as a product of what
looks like the difference

00:23:44.290 --> 00:23:48.050
quotient of f times the
difference quotient of g.

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:51.050
But you have to be
careful, because g of x

00:23:51.050 --> 00:23:53.210
could equal g of
