00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:57.240
you're dividing by 0 in this
basic idea we had up there,

00:23:57.240 --> 00:23:58.940
which is not allowed.

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:04.670
But you get around it by
using these functions which

00:24:04.670 --> 00:24:08.270
equal what you want as long
as you're not dividing by 0,

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:09.020
basically.

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:21.411
So that wraps it up for basic
properties of the derivative.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:32.960
And now, we're going to
move on to trying to prove

00:24:32.960 --> 00:24:34.040
the mean value theorem--

00:24:45.990 --> 00:24:48.855
the Alfred of this Batman tale.

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:56.880
But first, in order
to prove this,

00:24:56.880 --> 00:25:01.420
we'll need a result about
the derivative in relation

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:05.680
to certain relative minimum
and relative maximum.

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:08.125
So let me first define
what this means.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:20.750
Let S be a subset of R, f
be a function from S to R.

00:25:20.750 --> 00:25:35.700
We say f has a
relative max at c in S.

00:25:35.700 --> 00:25:40.490
If there exists
a delta positive,

00:25:40.490 --> 00:25:47.550
such that for all x in S, x
minus c is less than delta,

00:25:47.550 --> 00:25:50.570
then f of x is less
than or equal to f of c.

00:25:54.260 --> 00:25:56.870
So the picture
here, and then let

00:25:56.870 --> 00:26:12.420
me state that there's
analogous definition

00:26:12.420 --> 00:26:17.880
of relative min at c.

00:26:17.880 --> 00:26:19.500
You just take this
entire definition

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:22.560
and flip the inequality.

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:24.210
That's the definition
for relative min.

00:26:24.210 --> 00:26:27.660
So what this means
pictorially, so remember,

00:26:27.660 --> 00:26:30.600
we had this notion of
absolute min and absolute max.

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:36.480
An absolute max at a point
c means at every other point

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:39.750
in S, f of x lies below f of c.

00:26:39.750 --> 00:26:45.390
Here we're just saying, as long
as you're close to the point c,

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:47.450
then you lay below f of c.

00:26:47.450 --> 00:27:05.430
So let's say our function
looks something like that.

00:27:08.900 --> 00:27:21.040
So then, let's say we're
at this point here.

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:28.360
So this would be absolute
max, because the graph

00:27:28.360 --> 00:27:34.600
of the function sits below
the value of the function

00:27:34.600 --> 00:27:39.160
at this point for all x
in this interval a, b.

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:46.720
And then, here at this point,
we would have an absolute min,

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:49.630
because the rest of--

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:51.820
because the graph
of the function

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:58.050
sits above that point for
all x in this interval.

00:27:58.050 --> 00:28:06.090
But now, if I go
to this point, say,

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:12.320
this would be a relative
max, because why?

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:18.290
If I look at an interval--
small interval around it,

00:28:18.290 --> 00:28:20.120
and I look inside
this interval--

00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:22.200
there's too many
dashed lines going on.

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:24.080
So I'm going to erase this.

00:28:32.310 --> 00:28:34.530
Yeah, I'm just going to
do away with the dash.

00:28:34.530 --> 00:28:37.500
If I zoom in on just this
one piece of the graph,

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:44.260
then at this point,
the graph sits

00:28:44.260 --> 00:28:55.000
below this point inside
this little vertical strip.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.520
So this guy would
be a relative max.

00:28:57.520 --> 00:29:00.550
And then similarly,
at this point here,

00:29:00.550 --> 00:29:01.690
maybe it's-- let me--

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:14.990
so you can really see
what the graph is.

00:29:14.990 --> 00:29:18.300
I should have brought
different colors.

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:22.500
At this point, we
have a relative min.

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:27.960
Because nearby points sit
above the value of the function

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:29.760
evaluated at this point.

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:36.780
So relative max means
nearby points f sits below

00:29:36.780 --> 00:29:39.360
that f evaluated at that point.

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:41.190
And relative min is
the other way around.

00:29:49.550 --> 00:29:53.600
So I don't think
we need to belabor

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:56.333
the point of what relative
min relative maxes are.

00:29:56.333 --> 00:29:57.500
I think that's pretty clear.

00:30:06.990 --> 00:30:12.550
So the theorem is the following.

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:29.970
If f from a, b has a relative
min or max at a point

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:34.300
c strictly inside this closed
interval, in the open interval

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:52.340
a, b, then and f is
differentiable at c, then

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:54.470
f prime of c equals 0.

00:30:54.470 --> 00:30:56.330
And this is kind of
clear from this picture,

00:30:56.330 --> 00:30:58.880
although this might look
more like a sawtooth,

00:30:58.880 --> 00:31:01.610
but it shouldn't, that
the tangent at this point

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:03.260
is horizontal.

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:05.400
And the tangent at this
point is horizontal,

00:31:05.400 --> 00:31:09.770
which just is the expression
that we're just expressing

00:31:09.770 --> 00:31:11.840
that f prime of c equals 0.

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:14.840
Because f prime of c is supposed
to be the slope of the tangent.

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:31.240
So the idea of the proof is--

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:33.070
and we'll do it
for relative max.

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:36.820
Relative min you get
by taking minus f.

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:52.520
So we'll do it for suppose f
has a relative max at c in a, b.

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:04.440
Then so I'm just going
to draw a picture

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:07.410
to illustrate why
this is the case, so

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:09.610
or why what I'm about
to say is the case.

00:32:09.610 --> 00:32:13.650
So we have a, b, we have c.

00:32:13.650 --> 00:32:24.220
Then there exist delta
positive, say delta one,

00:32:24.220 --> 00:32:26.830
such that two things are true.

00:32:32.730 --> 00:32:42.510
x or c minus delta 1 c plus
delta 1 is contained in a, b.

00:32:42.510 --> 00:32:54.460
Two, for all x in c minus
delta 1, c plus delta 1,

00:32:54.460 --> 00:32:57.790
f of x is less than
or equal to f of c.

00:32:57.790 --> 00:33:04.120
So delta 1 is chosen
as the minimum of--

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:06.757
so maybe let me not
call it delta one,

00:33:06.757 --> 00:33:07.840
let me just call it delta.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:16.130
So first off, you know
that a, b, open interval,

00:33:16.130 --> 00:33:20.490
this is an open set which we've
encountered in the assignments.

00:33:20.490 --> 00:33:34.570
So you can find a
delta so that delta 0,

00:33:34.570 --> 00:33:37.480
say, so that this
interval centered

00:33:37.480 --> 00:33:39.310
at c is contained in a, b.

00:33:41.980 --> 00:33:46.540
Now, since f has a relative
maximum at this point,

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:49.090
there exist another
delta 1, say,

00:33:49.090 --> 00:33:57.710
so that if I'm
inside that interval,

00:33:57.710 --> 00:34:00.470
then f of x is less
than or equal to f of c

00:34:00.470 --> 00:34:03.140
for all x in that interval.

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:07.190
And I choose delta to be the
minimum of these two deltas.

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:12.370
And then I will
have a chosen delta

00:34:12.370 --> 00:34:16.435
so that c minus delta
c plus delta is--

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:26.264
so here, this one is--

00:34:34.840 --> 00:34:37.400
and then delta 0 shows them
so that that is contained.

00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:39.130
So I choose the minimum
of these deltas.

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:41.650
And this is the delta I
take for this statement.

00:34:45.600 --> 00:34:50.880
So now, the way we get
that the derivative is 0

00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:57.090
is, we're going to approach
c from above and from

00:34:57.090 --> 00:35:01.920
below and use the fact
that we have a relative max

00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:05.850
to show that the derivative is
both bigger than or equal to 0

00:35:05.850 --> 00:35:07.920
and less than or equal to 0.

00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:17.840
So let xn be c minus--

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:19.340
how did I write this--

00:35:19.340 --> 00:35:27.890
delta over 2n, which is in
the interval c minus delta c

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:28.730
for all n.

00:35:33.940 --> 00:35:38.290
Then what do we know?
xn, the limit as n

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:44.155
goes to infinity of c minus
delta over 2, n converges to c.

00:35:47.030 --> 00:35:53.750
So the derivative at c
is equal to the limit

00:35:53.750 --> 00:35:59.090
as n goes to infinity
of f of x sub n minus f

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:02.720
of c over x sub n minus c.

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:07.640
Now, what do we note?

00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:10.170
So x sub is in
this interval here,

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:12.470
which is contained in
this interval here.

00:36:12.470 --> 00:36:14.600
And therefore, f of
x sub n is always

00:36:14.600 --> 00:36:16.370
less than or equal to f of c.

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:20.915
So what's on top is always
less than or equal to 0.

00:36:23.890 --> 00:36:26.770
Now, x sub n is
always less than c.

00:36:26.770 --> 00:36:31.120
So this thing on bottom
is also less than 0.

00:36:31.120 --> 00:36:33.010
And therefore, something
that's less than

00:36:33.010 --> 00:36:35.770
or equal to 0 on top over
something that's less than 0

00:36:35.770 --> 00:36:39.010
on bottom must be bigger
than or equal to 0.

00:36:45.660 --> 00:36:48.510
So that's approaching
c from the left.

00:36:48.510 --> 00:36:55.200
If we approach c from
the right, delta over 2n

00:36:55.200 --> 00:37:05.190
which is contained in c, c
plus delta for all n, then

00:37:05.190 --> 00:37:09.030
xn converges to c.

00:37:09.030 --> 00:37:14.070
And if we look at f
prime of c, again, this

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:17.550
is equal to limit as
n goes to infinity

00:37:17.550 --> 00:37:23.040
of f of y sub n minus f
of c over y sub n minus c.

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:26.820
Again, f of c is a
relative maximum.

00:37:26.820 --> 00:37:30.870
So this thing on top is still
less than or equal to 0.

00:37:30.870 --> 00:37:32.760
And the thing on
bottom though, is now

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:37.140
since y sub n is bigger
than c, this is positive.

00:37:37.140 --> 00:37:40.710
So something on top is negative,
something on top is positive.

00:37:40.710 --> 00:37:43.290
So the limit must be negative.

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:49.540
So we've just shown
f prime of c is

00:37:49.540 --> 00:37:51.340
both bigger than or equal to 0.

00:37:51.340 --> 00:37:53.320
And that it's also less
than or equal to 0.

00:38:03.500 --> 00:38:07.170
And therefore, the derivative
is 0 at this point.

00:38:13.295 --> 00:38:15.170
And again, the proof
for a relative minimum

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:28.893
is very similar, except
that inequality flips signs.

00:38:28.893 --> 00:38:30.810
And therefore, you would
get this is less than

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:34.530
or equal to 0, this one would
be bigger than or equal to 0.

00:38:34.530 --> 00:38:38.400
But you still get f prime of
c is bounded between 0 and 0.

00:38:41.250 --> 00:38:49.680
So at a point where we have
a relative minimum strictly

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:55.450
inside the interval, the
derivative must be 0.

00:39:00.915 --> 00:39:03.290
And the fact that it happens
strictly inside the interval

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:04.100
is important.

00:39:04.100 --> 00:39:09.050
This is not necessarily
true if the relative max

00:39:09.050 --> 00:39:11.480
or relative min
happens at an endpoint.

00:39:11.480 --> 00:39:16.790
Think of f of x
equals x on 0, 1.

00:39:16.790 --> 00:39:20.090
Then it has a absolute minimum
at 0, absolute maximum at 1,

00:39:20.090 --> 00:39:23.060
and the derivative is 1
at both points, not 0.

00:39:23.060 --> 00:39:25.880
So this is only
for relative min,

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:28.670
relative maxes
that occur inside--

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:32.750
strictly inside the interval
that the function is defined on

00:39:32.750 --> 00:39:35.400
and where it's differentiable.

00:39:38.580 --> 00:39:49.310
So now, we have Rolle's
theorem, which is essentially

00:39:49.310 --> 00:39:53.720
the mean value theorem rotated.

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:55.970
We'll get the mean value
theorem from Rolle's theorem.

00:39:55.970 --> 00:40:07.500
And which states the following,
let f be from a, b to R,

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:08.700
be continuous.

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:23.430
So it's continuous at every
point in a, b, differentiable

00:40:23.430 --> 00:40:27.787
at every point inside of a, b.

00:40:27.787 --> 00:40:29.620
It could be differentiable
at the endpoints.

00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:30.120
That's fine.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:33.360
But it has to be differentiable
on the open interval a, b.

00:40:38.585 --> 00:40:43.710
If f of b, a equals
f of b equals 0,

00:40:43.710 --> 00:40:51.225
then there exists a point c
in the open interval a, b--

00:40:51.225 --> 00:40:53.950
and this is important--

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:58.570
such that f prime of c equals 0.

00:40:58.570 --> 00:41:02.200
And what's the what's the
picture that goes with this?

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:03.670
I'm sure you've seen it before.

