We draw a function that looks
kind of like sine or cosine.

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:20.530
But anyways, function
which is 0 here, 0 here.

00:41:20.530 --> 00:41:27.550
Then there has to exist a point
where the tangent is vertical.

00:41:27.550 --> 00:41:31.925
In fact, here it can occur
at two different points.

00:41:34.355 --> 00:41:35.730
But something
that's already kind

00:41:35.730 --> 00:41:38.160
of giving the game away as
far as how we'll prove this

00:41:38.160 --> 00:41:44.190
is, let's look at where
the function takes

00:41:44.190 --> 00:41:46.170
a maximum and a minimum.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:51.855
That is the heart of the proof.

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:58.050
And why can we--
why does it even

00:41:58.050 --> 00:42:00.180
have an absolute maximum
or absolute minimum?

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:05.030
So I guess I didn't
say this over there

00:42:05.030 --> 00:42:07.070
when I discussed relative
min and relative max.

00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:11.790
But an absolute maximum is
also a relative maximum.

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:15.305
And absolute minimum is
also a relative minimum.

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:23.230
So let me make this-- this
is kind of a late remark.

00:42:30.340 --> 00:42:48.260
Absolute max is a relative
max, absolute mins

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:49.310
is a relative min.

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:58.420
So this picture is kind of
given the game away already.

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:02.020
Let's look at where the
function takes a max and a min.

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:06.030
And why does f take
a max or a min?

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:08.430
It's because f is continuous
on this closed and bounded

00:43:08.430 --> 00:43:08.930
interval.

00:43:08.930 --> 00:43:13.050
This is something we proved when
we were discussing continuity,

00:43:13.050 --> 00:43:14.860
the min max theorem.

00:43:14.860 --> 00:43:18.510
So let's give the proof.

00:43:27.150 --> 00:43:42.260
Since f is continuous on a,
b, f achieves a relative max

00:43:42.260 --> 00:43:56.940
at some point c1 in a, b, and
relative min at c2 in a, b.

00:44:05.080 --> 00:44:09.705
If there exists an x--

00:44:09.705 --> 00:44:10.205
also.

00:44:15.700 --> 00:44:21.210
If of f of c1 is positive,
then what can you say?

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:24.290
Well, c1 cannot be
one of the endpoints,

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:29.240
because at the endpoints, f
of a equals f of b equals 0.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.630
This implies c1 is
in the open interval

00:44:35.630 --> 00:44:39.950
a, b, which implies by the
previous theorem, f prime

00:44:39.950 --> 00:44:42.890
of c1 equals 0.

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:47.250
So here you-- c equals c1.

00:44:51.990 --> 00:44:58.500
If I'm at the minimum now,
and this is less than 0,

00:44:58.500 --> 00:45:07.370
then again, this implies that
c2 is in the open interval a,

00:45:07.370 --> 00:45:15.300
b, which implies since f has
a minimum at c2, f prime of c2

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:17.310
equals 0 by the
previous theorem.

00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:19.380
And therefore, we
could take c equals c2.

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:29.930
If-- now, this is two cases--
f of c1, if either f of c1

00:45:29.930 --> 00:45:32.600
is positive or f of
c2 is less than 0,

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:42.920
then we have the result. If f of
c1 is less than or equal to 0,

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:46.040
is less than or
equal to f of c2,

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:50.270
now remember, f
achieves a max that c1.

00:45:50.270 --> 00:45:52.253
F achieves a min at c2.

