Sorry that I kind of fumbled
through that for a minute,

00:49:54.690 --> 00:49:57.370
but--

00:49:57.370 --> 00:49:58.870
OK.

00:49:58.870 --> 00:50:03.370
So for any function which
is 0 at the endpoints,

00:50:03.370 --> 00:50:09.130
there has to be a point in
between where the function is--

00:50:09.130 --> 00:50:12.040
the derivative of the
function equals 0.

00:50:12.040 --> 00:50:19.460
Now, again, we should come
back to when we see a theorem,

00:50:19.460 --> 00:50:21.640
we should pick it
apart a little bit

00:50:21.640 --> 00:50:23.275
to see what's
necessary, what's not.

00:50:26.898 --> 00:50:29.482
We had these two
hypotheses coming in,

00:50:29.482 --> 00:50:31.690
that if the function is
continuous and differentiable

00:50:31.690 --> 00:50:37.030
on this open interval a,
b, are these necessary?

00:50:37.030 --> 00:50:59.740
So for example, let's
say I have the function--

00:50:59.740 --> 00:51:05.560
if I look at the function 1
minus the absolute value of x.

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:17.360
So at minus 1, 1, 1, this
is a continuous function

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:25.305
on minus 1, 1.

00:51:28.920 --> 00:51:32.310
And f of minus 1
equals f of 1 equals 0.

00:51:32.310 --> 00:51:36.000
But there is no point where
f prime of c equals 0.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.160
What hypothesis did I leave
out for this function?

00:51:39.160 --> 00:51:40.320
The fact that it's--

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:42.930
the hypothesis that it's
differentiable at every point

00:51:42.930 --> 00:51:44.370
in between.

00:51:44.370 --> 00:51:46.200
This function is
not differentiable.

00:51:58.280 --> 00:52:01.340
But there's no point where
the derivative equals 0.

00:52:01.340 --> 00:52:05.420
So this example tells
you that the hypothesis

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:10.550
that the function
is differentiable

00:52:10.550 --> 00:52:14.750
on the interval
minus 1, 1, or a, b,

00:52:14.750 --> 00:52:17.585
is necessary for the
theorem to be true.

00:52:17.585 --> 00:52:18.710
That's what I'm getting at.

00:52:26.590 --> 00:52:30.610
Now, the other hypothesis
that the function

00:52:30.610 --> 00:52:37.420
is continuous on the closed
interval is also necessary.

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:38.455
Let's say I look at--

00:52:43.470 --> 00:52:46.510
and this is pretty easy to
come up with a counter-example,

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:47.640
if I don't assume that.

00:52:54.180 --> 00:53:06.820
Let's take the
function which is--

00:53:22.480 --> 00:53:25.810
the function that's x minus
1 for x not equal to minus 1,

00:53:25.810 --> 00:53:29.470
and 0 for x equal to minus 1.

00:53:29.470 --> 00:53:31.240
So does is this
function look like?

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:51.860
So this function here is
differentiable on minus 1, 1,

00:53:51.860 --> 00:53:56.600
f of minus 1 equals
f of 1 equals 0.

00:53:56.600 --> 00:54:04.250
But again, there's no
point c in minus 1, 1 so

00:54:04.250 --> 00:54:08.660
that f prime of c equals 0.

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:13.940
Because the derivative in
between minus 1, 1 is just 1.

00:54:13.940 --> 00:54:17.780
So both of these
hypotheses, that f

00:54:17.780 --> 00:54:20.690
is continuous on the closed
interval and differentiable

00:54:20.690 --> 00:54:23.720
on the open interval, are
necessary for this theorem

00:54:23.720 --> 00:54:24.590
to be true.

00:54:24.590 --> 00:54:27.827
If you drop either
of those hypotheses,

00:54:27.827 --> 00:54:28.910
then the theorem is false.

00:54:45.800 --> 00:54:49.340
So let's rotate this
picture here and arrive

00:54:49.340 --> 00:54:50.480
at the mean value theorem.

00:55:03.120 --> 00:55:09.040
Let f from a, b to
R be continuous.

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:16.600
So it's continuous on the closed
interval a, b, differentiable

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:17.100
on a, b.

00:55:25.750 --> 00:55:29.800
Then there exists a c
in the open interval

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:40.166
a, b such that f prime of c--

00:55:40.166 --> 00:55:41.410
let me write it this way--

00:55:47.002 --> 00:55:54.800
f of b minus f of
a times b minus a.

00:55:58.500 --> 00:56:04.560
So why do I refer to it as a
rotated picture and shifted

00:56:04.560 --> 00:56:05.820
version of Rolle's theorem?

00:56:08.560 --> 00:56:11.060
So there's a, b.

00:56:11.060 --> 00:56:14.450
Here's f of a, f of b.

00:56:14.450 --> 00:56:20.860
And let's say that's
how the function looks.

00:56:20.860 --> 00:56:27.300
Now, the slope of the line
connecting f of b to f of a

00:56:27.300 --> 00:56:29.602
is exactly f of b minus f of a.

00:56:34.090 --> 00:56:40.080
So the slope of that line
is f of b minus f of a.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:45.980
And what we're stating is
that there's a point c,

00:56:45.980 --> 00:56:53.050
so that the tangent at that
point is parallel to that line,

00:56:53.050 --> 00:57:00.220
has the same slope as the line
connecting f of b to f of a.

00:57:09.480 --> 00:57:13.800
So this theorem really does
reduce to Rolle's theorem.

00:57:13.800 --> 00:57:23.020
So let me define a
function g from a, b

00:57:23.020 --> 00:57:30.770
to R, which satisfies the
hypotheses of Rolle's theorem

00:57:30.770 --> 00:57:35.050
and will give us what
we want, basically.

00:57:35.050 --> 00:57:43.270
So g of x equals f
of x minus f of b,

00:57:43.270 --> 00:57:54.290
plus f of b minus f of a over
b minus a times b minus x.

00:57:57.960 --> 00:58:00.210
Basically, what this
function g does is,

00:58:00.210 --> 00:58:04.470
it takes the function
now and rotates it,

00:58:04.470 --> 00:58:07.500
and shifts it down, so that f--

00:58:07.500 --> 00:58:10.215
these two points then
coincide and give you 0.

00:58:15.920 --> 00:58:24.190
Then g is continuous on
the closed interval a, b.

00:58:24.190 --> 00:58:24.690
Why?

00:58:24.690 --> 00:58:27.960
Because it's a sum of two
continuous functions on a, b.

00:58:27.960 --> 00:58:30.570
f of x is continuous on a, b.

00:58:30.570 --> 00:58:32.220
And this is just a constant.

00:58:32.220 --> 00:58:33.580
That's just a constant.

00:58:33.580 --> 00:58:35.580
This is a polynomial.

00:58:35.580 --> 00:58:47.500
So g is continuous on a, b,
and differentiable on a, b,

00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:49.240
again, because f is.

00:58:49.240 --> 00:58:52.630
F is differentiable on
the open interval a, b.

00:58:52.630 --> 00:58:55.240
This part is
differentiable everywhere

00:58:55.240 --> 00:58:59.350
so the sum of two differentiable
functions is differential.

00:58:59.350 --> 00:59:01.030
So g of x is
differentiable on a, b.

00:59:04.580 --> 00:59:09.010
So continuous on a, b and
differentiable on a, b.

00:59:12.902 --> 00:59:15.110
And since I said, we're
going to use Rolle's theorem,

00:59:15.110 --> 00:59:16.767
let's compute g of a.

00:59:16.767 --> 00:59:22.280
This is equal to f
of a minus f of b,

00:59:22.280 --> 00:59:30.800
plus f of b minus f of a, over
b minus a, times b minus a.

00:59:30.800 --> 00:59:32.150
That cancels with that.

00:59:32.150 --> 00:59:34.770
Minus f of b
cancels with f of b.

00:59:34.770 --> 00:59:37.790
f of a cancels with minus
f of a, and we get 0.

00:59:41.391 --> 00:59:45.080
And then, g of b, this
is even easier to see.

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:46.580
If I just stick
this in, this is f

00:59:46.580 --> 00:59:56.690
of b minus f of b plus f of b
minus f of a, over b minus a,

00:59:56.690 --> 00:59:58.460
b minus b.

00:59:58.460 --> 01:00:00.290
And this also equals 0.

01:00:00.290 --> 01:00:02.930
So g of a and g of b are 0.

01:00:02.930 --> 01:00:05.180
The function is continuous
on the closed interval.

01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:07.160
It's differentiable
on the open interval.

01:00:07.160 --> 01:00:15.073
And therefore, by
Rolle's theorem--

01:00:15.073 --> 01:00:17.490
I think there's supposed to
be some sort of accent over O,

01:00:17.490 --> 01:00:22.360
but I can't remember, and
I've forgotten it already.

01:00:22.360 --> 01:00:28.600
By Rolle's theorem, there
exist a point c in a, b, such

01:00:28.600 --> 01:00:40.850
that 0 is equal to g prime
of c, which is equal to--

01:00:40.850 --> 01:00:43.430
we take g and actually
compute what the derivative is

01:00:43.430 --> 01:00:49.010
at c, is equal to f prime of c.

01:00:49.010 --> 01:00:51.650
That's a constant
derivative of that is 0.

01:00:51.650 --> 01:00:55.310
This times this, the derivative
of x evaluated at c just

01:00:55.310 --> 01:01:05.590
gives me minus f of b minus
f of a, times b minus a.

01:01:05.590 --> 01:01:08.700
And that's it.

01:01:08.700 --> 01:01:12.330
0 is equal to f prime
of c minus what we want.

01:01:12.330 --> 01:01:15.485
We move that to the other side,
multiply through by b minus a,

01:01:15.485 --> 01:01:16.110
and we're done.

01:01:34.790 --> 01:01:41.480
So some first very
nice applications

01:01:41.480 --> 01:01:43.160
of the mean value
theorem, which I

01:01:43.160 --> 01:01:46.280
think you learned from
calculus are the following.

01:02:13.080 --> 01:02:18.080
Let f from I to R
be differentiable,

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:24.010
meaning it's differentiable at
every point in the interval I.

01:02:24.010 --> 01:02:27.130
Then we have two conclusions.

01:02:27.130 --> 01:02:36.860
f is increasing, meaning
we recall what that means,

01:02:36.860 --> 01:02:42.860
for f to be increasing, that
means that if x is less than y,

01:02:42.860 --> 01:02:47.150
this implies f of x is less
than or equal to f of y.

01:02:50.960 --> 01:03:01.160
This is equivalent
to for all x in I,

01:03:01.160 --> 01:03:03.710
f prime of x is bigger
than or equal to 0.

01:03:03.710 --> 01:03:06.890
So remember, f prime
is the rate of change.

01:03:06.890 --> 01:03:08.850
If the rate of change
is always non-negative,

01:03:08.850 --> 01:03:10.590
then f has to be growing.

01:03:10.590 --> 01:03:19.970
But this says, f is decreasing,
meaning x less than y

01:03:19.970 --> 01:03:25.760
implies f of x is bigger
than or equal to f of y.

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:30.080
This is equivalent to since
a function is increasing

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:32.780
if and only if minus
f is decreasing,

01:03:32.780 --> 01:03:34.250
this inequality should flip.

01:03:52.570 --> 01:03:56.950
So I'm going to do increasing--
decreasing follows from number

01:03:56.950 --> 01:03:58.870
one by taking minus f.

01:04:09.130 --> 01:04:13.040
So how much time do I have?

01:04:13.040 --> 01:04:13.810
I still have time.

01:04:21.030 --> 01:04:28.012
So suppose first that f prime
of x is always non-negative.

01:04:32.120 --> 01:04:43.550
Let a, b be in I.
[SNEEZES] Excuse me.

01:04:47.872 --> 01:04:50.330
We now want to show f of a is
less than or equal to f of b.

01:04:55.390 --> 01:05:01.560
Then f is continuous on
this smaller interval a, b.

01:05:01.560 --> 01:05:02.400
Why?

01:05:02.400 --> 01:05:04.950
Because f is differentiable
at every point in I.

01:05:04.950 --> 01:05:11.070
And therefore, it is
continuous at every point in I.

01:05:11.070 --> 01:05:24.250
So in particular on this smaller
interval, and differentiable

01:05:24.250 --> 01:05:33.190
on a, b, which implies
there exists a c in a, b--

01:05:33.190 --> 01:05:42.370
So by the mean value
theorem, such that f

01:05:42.370 --> 01:05:49.630
of b minus f of a equals f
prime of c times b minus a.

01:05:49.630 --> 01:05:53.410
And now, since the derivative
is always non-negative

01:05:53.410 --> 01:05:57.400
and b minus a is positive, this
is bigger than or equal to 0.

01:05:57.400 --> 01:05:59.020
I.e.

01:05:59.020 --> 01:06:01.825
if a b minus f of a is
bigger than or equal to 0.

01:06:07.280 --> 01:06:08.840
So we prove in one direction.

01:06:08.840 --> 01:06:19.790
We've proven that if you
like that the function's

01:06:19.790 --> 01:06:22.400
derivative being non-negative
implies that the function is

01:06:22.400 --> 01:06:24.910
increasing.

01:06:24.910 --> 01:06:26.760
So now let's prove the
opposite direction.

01:06:35.010 --> 01:06:54.100
So suppose f is
increasing and c is in I.

01:06:54.100 --> 01:07:07.100
Let xn be a sequence in I,
such that xn converges to c.

01:07:07.100 --> 01:07:09.695
And one of two things holds.

01:07:12.770 --> 01:07:28.580
And either let's say, a,
all n xn is less than c,

01:07:28.580 --> 01:07:32.900
or b, all n xn is bigger than c.

01:07:32.900 --> 01:07:35.480
And we can always find such
a sequence given a point

01:07:35.480 --> 01:07:39.920
C in the interval I.

01:07:39.920 --> 01:07:48.520
So if I, so let's say,
it's a closed interval.

01:07:48.520 --> 01:07:51.280
And c is in here.

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:55.780
Then we can find a sequence
xn converging to c,

01:07:55.780 --> 01:07:57.505
approaching c from the left.

01:08:00.430 --> 01:08:03.010
If c is one of the
endpoints, then we

01:08:03.010 --> 01:08:06.520
can find a sequence from I
approaching c from the right.

01:08:06.520 --> 01:08:07.900
That's b.

01:08:07.900 --> 01:08:09.790
And the same thing
if c is over here we

01:08:09.790 --> 01:08:13.330
can find a sequence approaching
c, strictly from the left.

01:08:15.940 --> 01:08:18.400
So there always exists
such a sequence.

01:08:28.960 --> 01:08:29.700
Always exists.

01:08:32.979 --> 01:08:38.795
And this is because,
I is an interval.

01:08:53.500 --> 01:09:00.750
And if the sequence satisfies
case a, and we look at f prime,

01:09:00.750 --> 01:09:08.569
then we get that f
of xn is less than

01:09:08.569 --> 01:09:14.120
or equal to f of c for all n.

01:09:14.120 --> 01:09:17.090
And let me in fact write this
a little bit differently.

01:09:17.090 --> 01:09:19.850
Since-- so here we're
using that f as increasing.

01:09:28.880 --> 01:09:34.689
Since f is increasing,
which implies

01:09:34.689 --> 01:09:42.700
for all n, f of xn minus f
of c over x of n minus c--

01:09:42.700 --> 01:09:48.729
now, this thing on top is
negative. xn is less than c.

01:09:48.729 --> 01:09:53.830
So this thing on the
bottom is also negative.

01:09:53.830 --> 01:09:57.940
And therefore, this
thing is, positive--

01:09:57.940 --> 01:10:00.860
non-negative, I mean.

01:10:00.860 --> 01:10:03.020
And therefore, the limit
must also be negative.

01:10:05.610 --> 01:10:08.280
But that limit is just a
derivative evaluated at c.

01:10:21.070 --> 01:10:23.230
And case b is kind of similar.

01:10:23.230 --> 01:10:27.040
I mean, not kind of, it is.

01:10:27.040 --> 01:10:32.500
In case b, we get that
for all n, f of xn,

01:10:32.500 --> 01:10:34.600
now, since x tends
to the right of c--

01:10:37.890 --> 01:10:39.140
let me write it this way.

01:10:42.110 --> 01:10:46.040
This minus f of c is
bigger than or equal to 0,

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:51.950
which implies that
f prime of c, which

01:10:51.950 --> 01:10:56.360
is the limit as n goes
to infinity of f of xn

01:10:56.360 --> 01:11:01.040
minus f of c over xn minus c.

01:11:01.040 --> 01:11:02.798
What's on top is non-negative.

01:11:02.798 --> 01:11:04.340
And what's on bottom
is non-negative,

01:11:04.340 --> 01:11:08.120
because xn is bigger than c.

01:11:08.120 --> 01:11:12.382
So bigger than 0, bigger
than 0, bigger than 0.

01:11:19.660 --> 01:11:22.210
Thus in either
case, we get that f

01:11:22.210 --> 01:11:24.533
prime of c is bigger
than or equal to 0.

01:11:28.915 --> 01:11:31.290
And therefore, we've proven
that the derivative is always

01:11:31.290 --> 01:11:33.540
non-negative.

01:11:33.540 --> 01:11:36.570
So that's one.

01:11:36.570 --> 01:11:48.870
And two, f is
decreasing if and only

01:11:48.870 --> 01:11:56.910
if the function minus f is
increasing, which by what

01:11:56.910 --> 01:12:02.610
we've done from part one is if
and only if minus f prime of x

01:12:02.610 --> 01:12:07.530
is bigger than or equal to
0 for all x in I. And then,

01:12:07.530 --> 01:12:15.750
multiplying through by this
minus 1 gives me number two.

01:12:22.570 --> 01:12:26.620
And so, let me make one last--

01:12:26.620 --> 01:12:28.960
I know it's taboo to
write on the back part.

01:12:28.960 --> 01:12:30.610
But I'm going to do it anyways.

01:12:30.610 --> 01:12:33.325
We have the very simple
theorem which now follows.

01:12:38.830 --> 01:12:47.890
Let f from I to R
be differentiable,

01:12:47.890 --> 01:12:53.630
then f is constant.

01:12:53.630 --> 01:12:58.690
So f of x equals f of
y for all x and y in I,

01:12:58.690 --> 01:13:03.770
if and only if the
derivative is identically 0.

01:13:09.870 --> 01:13:25.630
So f is constant if
and only if f is both

01:13:25.630 --> 01:13:29.690
increasing and decreasing.

01:13:37.030 --> 01:13:40.600
Because it satisfies the
equality sign in both of those.

01:13:40.600 --> 01:13:46.960
And by what we've done now,
this means for all x in I,

01:13:46.960 --> 01:13:52.480
if prime of x is bigger
than or equal to 0, and--

01:13:52.480 --> 01:13:54.520
that's for the
increasing part-- f prime

01:13:54.520 --> 01:13:55.990
of x is less than or equal to 0.

01:13:58.610 --> 01:14:09.530
And therefore, this
is equivalent to f

01:14:09.530 --> 01:14:10.760
prime of x equals 0.

01:14:17.820 --> 01:14:20.030
So we'll stop there.

